Whenever I speak in public, regardless of what I say, there is a diatribe of insults on social media demanding my withdrawal, denouncing the policies of the center, telling me that I shouldn’t be in the Labour Party.
I'm not the only one who's experienced it.
Indeed, I know that I am more fortunate than some of my colleagues, since comments about me tend to be political.
I am amazed at the professionalism and determination of colleagues who face a torrent of sexist or racist insults on a daily basis, but never run away.
One of the most disappointing aspects of this political era is the normalization of insults.
Last week, Jeremy Corbyn said the Labour Party should promote a culture of tolerance.
The reality is that we no longer have that wide range of opinions and, with every "censorship" motion or every change in selection rules, the party becomes narrower.
In the last two years, I’ve received a lot of advice that advised me to keep my head down and not make me hear so much and so “it would be okay.”
But I didn't get into politics to do that.
Since I joined the Labour Party 32 years ago as a high school student, motivated by the negligence of the Thatcher government that left the classroom of my comprehensive school literally in ruins, I have tried to support the improvement of public services for those who need it most, either as a councillor or as a government minister.
I have never hidden my political ideas, not even in the last election.
It is impossible for anyone in Nottingham East to ignore my political stances or the areas in which I disagreed with current leaders.
The only thing I would say to those who promoted Friday’s motion is that I don’t understand this desire to waste time and energy with questions about my fidelity to the leader of the Labour Party when the country heads to a Brexit that will affect homes, businesses and public services.
The real message is not for Nottingham Momentum, but for the voters, whether they are from the Labour Party or not: I am proud to serve you and I promise that no threat of withdrawal or political opportunism will stop me from acting on what I think is best for all of you.
Chris Leslie is Member of Parliament for Nottingham East
