John Edward: Language skills are fundamental to the citizens of the world
Scotland’s independent educational centres have a track record of academic excellence that has continued in 2018 with another set of extraordinary exam results that is reinforced by individual and collective successes harvested in the fields of sport, art, music and other community projects.
With more than 30,000 students across Scotland, these centers, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Colleges (SCIS), strive to deliver the best level of service to students and parents.
Independent colleges aim to prepare their students to continue their higher education studies, for the career they choose and for the place they occupy as citizens of the world.
As an educational sector that can design and implement a tailored curriculum, it is noted that modern languages remain a popular and desired subject in centers.
Nelson Mandela once said, “If you speak to a man in a language he understands, the message comes to his head.
If you speak to him in his tongue, he reaches to his heart.”
This is a powerful reminder that if you want to build relationships and build trust with people from other countries, you cannot rely solely on English.
If we take into account the recent results of this year’s exams, we can see that languages are at the top of the rankings, with the highest approval rates in independent colleges.
In total, 68% of students who studied foreign languages received an A, the highest grade.
The data, collected from the 74 centres that are part of SCIS, showed that 72% of students obtained an A in Mandarin, while 72% of those who studied German, 69% of those who studied French and 63% of those who studied Spanish also obtained an A.
This demonstrates that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages by considering them as a fundamental competence that both children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Currently, it is considered that, as a subject, languages are at the same level as CTIM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the study plans of independent colleges and everywhere.
A 2014 survey by the UK Commission on Employment and Skills revealed that 17 % of the reasons for employers’ difficulties in covering jobs were attributable to a lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are increasingly indispensable in preparing young people for their future careers.
Possible job opportunities that require languages are on the rise, so these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the career one chooses, if you have learned a second language, you will have a real advantage in the future thanks to a competition like this, which will last a lifetime.
Being able to communicate directly with people from foreign countries will allow that person to automatically advance to competition.
According to a survey conducted by YouGov among more than 4000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75% of them did not speak any foreign language well enough to maintain a conversation. It was also found that the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage, 15%, was French.
For this reason, investing in language teaching is now important for children today.
If they know several languages, especially those in developing economies, children will be equipped to have better opportunities to find quality employment.
In Scotland, each school will teach different languages.
Some centres will focus on the most classic modern languages, while others will teach the languages considered most important for the UK by 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever the interests of a child, in independent schools you can always choose between several languages taught by teaching staff specialized in this matter.
Scotland’s independent educational centres dedicate all their efforts to providing a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills needed to succeed, whatever the future holds for them.
At present, it is undeniable that, in a global business environment, languages continue to be of vital importance for the future of the country, so this should be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages should be considered "competences for international communication".
Independent schools will continue to offer these options, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
We have to do it right.
John Edward is the Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Colleges
