North Korea says there is "no chance" that they will disarm first unilaterally if they do not have confidence
On Saturday, North Korea’s foreign minister informed the United Nations that the continuation of the sanctions deepened its distrust of the United States and that there was no possibility of its country relinquishing nuclear weapons unilaterally under such circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the International Organization’s Annual General Assembly that North Korea had taken “important measures of goodwill” over the past year, such as stopping nuclear and missile tests, dismantling facilities for nuclear tests and committing to the non-proliferation of nuclear weapons and technology.
“However, we have not received any similar response from the United States,” he said.
“If we don’t have confidence in the United States, we can’t have confidence in our national security, and in those circumstances, there’s no way we can disarm unilaterally first.”
While Ri reiterated North Korea’s known complaints about Washington’s resistance to a “phased” denuclearization formula that rewards the country as it steps in step by step, his statement is important, as he did not simply reject a unilateral denuclearization, as Pyongyang has done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump after the first summit between an active U.S. president and a North Korean leader on June 12 in Singapore, when Kim pledged to work for the “nuclearization of the Korean peninsula” and Trump guaranteed North Korea’s security.
North Korea has pursued the official end of the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has said that Pyongyang should relinquish its nuclear weapons first.
Washington has also resisted calls to soften international sanctions on North Korea.
“The United States has insisted on denuclearization in the first place and has increased pressure through sanctions in order to achieve its purpose in a coercive way, even by putting objections to a declaration of war termination,” Ri said.
“The idea that sanctions can make us fall on our knees is a chimera of people who don’t know us.
The problem is that the continuation of sanctions deepens our distrust.”
Ri made no mention of the plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, announced by the U.S. leader to the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the minister highlighted three meetings held between Kim and Moon Jae, the leader of South Korea, over the past five months, and added: “If South Korea had been the party interested in denuclearization instead of the United States, denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not be in a stagnation.”
Even so, Ri’s tone of speech was radically different from last year’s speech, when he told the UN General Assembly that it was inevitable to direct North Korea’s missiles to U.S. soil after the “evil president” Trump, on a suicide mission, called Kim a “missile man.”
This year at the United Nations, Trump, who last year threatened to “totally destroy” North Korea, praised Kim for his courage in moving toward disarmament, but said there was still much to be done and that sanctions needed to continue until North Korea denuclearized.
On Wednesday, Trump said there was no set deadline for this: “We can take two years, three years or five months, no matter.”
China and Russia argue that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for its advances.
However, as U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the UN Security Council on Thursday: “The imposition of Security Council sanctions must continue vigorously and without breach until we realize the definitive and fully verified denuclearization.”
The Security Council has unanimously imposed sanctions on North Korea since 2006, in an attempt to cut funding for Pyongyang's ballistic and nuclear missile programs.
Pompeo spoke with Ri outside the UN General Assembly and later commented that he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare a second summit.
Pompeo has already visited North Korea three times this year, but his last trip was not good.
He left Pyongyang in July saying progress had been made, but, a few hours later, North Korea denounced that its "requirements were those of a mobster."
At a meeting with Moon this month, North Korea pledged to dismantle a missile site and a nuclear complex if the United States applied “corresponding measures.”
He said Kim had told him that the “corresponding measures” he was looking for were the security guarantees Trump had promised in Singapore and steps toward normalizing relations with Washington.
Harvard students take a course on how to get enough rest
Thanks to a new course taught this year at Harvard University, all college students sleep more in an attempt to fight the growing masculine culture of studying all night drinking caffeine.
One professor found that the number one university students in the world usually have no idea about the basic care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard School of Medicine, and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital designed the course, is believed to be the first of its kind in the U.S.
Their motivation to start the course came after giving a talk about how sleep deprivation affects learning.
“At the end of the course, a girl approached me and asked me why she just learned about this now, in her final year.
He said no one had ever told him about the importance of sleep, which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, taught for the first time this year, explains the basics of how good sleep habits contribute to academic and sports performance, as well as improving overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard School of Medicine and executive director of the university’s health services, said the university decided to introduce the course after discovering that students were barely sleeping during the week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one section, there is an image of a bedroom, where students click on coffee cups, curtains, sneakers, and books that inform them of the effects of caffeine and light, as well as the impact of lack of sleep on sports performance and the importance of establishing a routine to go to sleep.
In another section, participants are told how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, embolism, depression, and cancer.
Then, a campus icon with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily routines.
“We know it’s not going to change the behavior of the students right away.
However, we believe they have a right to know, just as anyone has a right to know the health effects of smoking tobacco,” added Professor Czeisler.
He claimed that the culture of pride for “sleeping the night on candles” still exists and added that modern technology and the increasing pressure that students are subjected to meant that sleep deprivation was a growing problem.
Sleeping long enough and a good quality sleep should be the “secret weapon” of students to combat stress, fatigue and anxiety; even to avoid gaining weight, as sleep deprivation causes the brain to generate a feeling of hunger, so they want to eat all the time.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studies chemical and physics biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course after attending one of his classes the previous year during his first year at Harvard.
He noted that the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to extend it to the entire campus.
He expects the next step to be to ask all graduate students to complete a similar study program before joining the competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler’s recommendation is for students to think about setting an alarm to go to bed and another to wake up, and to be aware of the harmful effects of “blue light” emitting the screens of electrical appliances and LEDs, which can alter the rhythms that would paradoxically end up having problems.
