HIV/AIDS: China reports 14% more new cases
China has announced a 14 percent increase in the number of citizens living with HIV and AIDS.
More than 820,000 people are affected in the country, according to health authorities.
In the second quarter of 2018 alone, some 40,000 new cases were reported.
The vast majority of these were sexually infected, which is a change from the past.
Traditionally, HIV spread rapidly across parts of China as a result of infected blood transfusions.
However, the number of people contracting HIV in this way has been reduced in its entirety, Chinese health authorities said at a congress in Yunnan province.
Each year, the number of people living with HIV and AIDS in China increases by about 100,000.
Sexual transmission of HIV is a serious problem in China’s LGBT community.
Homosexuality was decriminalized in China in 1997, but the LGBTQ group suffers a lot of discrimination.
Because of the country’s conservative values, studies have estimated that between 70 and 90 percent of men who have sex with other men will end up marrying women.
Many of the transmissions of diseases are due to the lack of adequate protection in these relationships.
Since 2003, the Chinese government has promised universal access to HIV medicines as part of an attempt to address the problem.
