The National Trust is spying on the secret life of bats
This new research, which has been carried out in a state in the Scottish Highlands, seeks to discover how bats use the landscape in their search for food.
Everything that is discovered is expected to shed more light on the behavior of the only flying mammals and help guide upcoming conservation activities.
The study, conducted by the National Trust for Scotland, will follow common bats and sopranos, as well as Daubenton’s coastal bats and long-eared browns from Inverewe’s gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed in strategic locations of the property to track bat activities during the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile investigations with portable detectors.
Experts will analyze the sounds that are collected in the recordings to discover the frequency of calls from bats and what species do it.
A report and a habitat map will then be produced to create a detailed picture of the environment and its behavior.
Rob Dewar, Nature Conservation Advisor for NTS, hopes the results will reveal which areas of habitat are most important for bats and how each species uses them.
This information will determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as grassland creation and how forests should be maintained for bats and other associated species.
Flea populations in Scotland and the United Kingdom have declined considerably in the last century.
They are under threat from the construction and development that affects their nests and the loss of their habitat.
Wind turbines and electrical wiring can also pose a risk to them, as can insecticide papers and other chemical treatments of building materials or domestic cat attacks.
The bats are not really blind,
But because of their night hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes to achieve their goal.
They use a sophisticated echolocation technique that locates ants and obstacles on their flight route.
The NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land across the country, takes the issue of bats very seriously.
It has ten experts trained in the field, who are dedicated to conducting regular surveys, nest inspections and, occasionally, rescues.
The organization has even inaugurated the first and only bat reserve in Scotland in the state of Thrave in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of Scotland’s ten bat species.
The director of the property, David Thompson, says it is the ideal territory for them.
“Here at Thrave, we have a fantastic bat area,” he said.
“We have old buildings, many veteran trees and all the right habitat.
However, there is still a lot unknown about bats, so the work we do here and on other properties will help us better understand what they need to develop.”
It underlines the importance of checking for bats before carrying out maintenance tasks within the properties, as a breeding colony can be involuntarily destroyed and 400 females and pups could be killed, which would annihilate an entire local population.
Fleas are protected and it is illegal to kill, harass or disturb them, as well as destroy their colonies.
Elisabeth Ferrell, the Scottish officer in charge of the Bat Conservation Trust, has encouraged the public to collaborate.
“We still have a lot to learn about bats and many other species that we don’t know how their populations evolve.”
