Both charges entail a possible death penalty, according to the court document.
Several weeks after the attack, a federal grand jury brought to Saipov a charge of 22 charges that included eight charges of organized crime-assisted murder, which federal prosecutors often use in these cases, and a charge of violence and destruction of motor vehicles.
The attack required “substantial planning and premeditation,” according to prosecutors, who described the way Saipov carried out it as “atrocious, cruel and depraved.”
"Sayfullo Habibullaevic Saipov caused injuries, damages and losses to the families and friends of Diego Enrique Angelini, Nicholas Cleves, Ann-Laure Decadt, Darren Drake, Ariel Erlij, Hernan Ferruchi, Hernan Diego Mendoza and Alejandro Damian Pagnocco".
Five of the victims were tourists from Argentina.
It’s been a decade since New York’s Southern District filed a death penalty case.
The defendant, Khalid Barnes, was found guilty of murdering two drug traffickers, but was eventually sentenced to life in prison in September 2009.
The last time a death penalty was executed in a federal New York case was to Julius and Ethel Rosenberg in 1953. This marriage was executed after they were convicted of conspiracy to commit espionage for the Soviet Union during the Cold War two years earlier.
The two Rosenbergs were executed in the electric chair on June 19, 1953.
Saipov, an immigrant from Uzbekistan, demonstrated his lack of remorse during the days and months following the attack, according to court documents.
According to police, he told investigators he felt good about what he had done.
