Red tide update: concentrations in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota decrease
The new report by the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows a general reduction in red tidal concentrations in areas of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, irregular flowering conditions are being reported in areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties, suggesting a reduction in concentrations.
The red tide flowering spans approximately 130 miles of coastline from Pinellas County to the north to Lee County to the south.
Irregular plots can be found about 10 miles off the coast of Hillsborough County, but in fewer sites if compared to last week.
Red tide has also been detected in Pasco County.
Over the past week, average concentrations have been reported in Pinellas County and its coast, low to high concentrations on the Hillsborough County coast, bottom to high concentrations in Manatee County, bottom to high concentrations in Sarasota County and its coast, bottom to middle concentrations.
Respiratory irritation issues continue to be reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
There have been no reports of respiratory irritation issues in Northwest Florida over the past week.
